The internet works as a global network of computers connected together. When you enter a website (like google.com), your device sends a request through your internet service provider (ISP) to a system called DNS (Domain Name System), which translates the website name into an IP address. This IP address identifies the server where the website is hosted.

Your request travels across multiple networks using routers, reaches the server, and the server sends back the website data (HTML, images, etc.). Your browser then displays this data as a webpage. All of this happens in milliseconds using standard protocols like HTTP/HTTPS.

Interview:

The internet works by sending requests from a client to a server using IP addresses and protocols like HTTP, with DNS translating domain names into IP addresses, enabling data to be exchanged and displayed as web pages.
